Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: Control module positive rails and switch/indicator branches (modules 1–8),
DESCRIPTION: With the battery installed and referenced to its negative terminal, measure DC voltage on the positive line at the input and output of each control module and across each switch when it is in the ON position. Also probe across each red indicator LED/resistor pair. Confirm whether 12 V is present at the module inputs and whether it propagates through each switch to the next module. Note any module where the positive rail voltage drops or where an ON switch still shows a significant voltage difference across its contacts (indicating an internal open).,
RESULT: 12 V is present on the positive input, switch, and output lines of Control Cubes 1–5, and the green LED/resistor parts are missing on all cubes. At Control Cube 6, the input positive cable shows 12 V on one end but its other end is disconnected from Switch 6, and no voltage appears on the switch or output; cubes 7 and 8 also show 0 V on their inputs, switches, and outputs. No polarity inversions are indicated in the reported measurements.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:34:06 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Internal connection between positive input terminal and switch in Control Module 6'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that the PSU + output is at 12 V and that this 12 V propagates correctly through control modules 1–5. At Control Module 6, 12 V is present only at the incoming positive cable terminal, but it does not appear on the switch input or on the module’s positive output; cubes 7 and 8 therefore also read 0 V. The test report explicitly notes that the input positive cable’s other end is disconnected from Switch 6. This localizes the open circuit to the internal positive feed within Control Module 6 (from its input terminal to the switch/rail). This open prevents current from reaching the load, so repairing/replacing this internal connection in Control Module 6 should restore normal operation.'
